IN THE 1940'S NYC BUILT PUBLIC LIBRARIES.
RAYMOND CLARK TELLS THE STORY OF ONE SUCH LIBRARY.
AS A CHILD RAYMOND THOUGHT HIS FAMILY WAS RICH, HIS MOM AND DAD TOLD HIM THAT NO THEY WERE POOR.
ONCE THE LIBRARY WAS BUILT DAD BECAME THE CUSTODIAN.
WE GOT TO LIVE IN THE LIBRARY THEN.
AS A CHILD HE WAS ASHAMED OF HIS HOME.
BUT IT WAS GREAT AS HE HAD MORE BOOKS THAN ANYONE ELSE.
HE COULD GET UP IN THE MIDDLE OF THE NIGHT AND GO READ A BOOK ON ANY SUBJECT.
IT WAS HARD DURING THE DAY BECAUSE HE HAD TO BE QUIET, BUT AT NIGHT HE WAS THE ONLY KID AND COULD RUN AND SCREAM.
DUE TO LIVING IN THE LIBRARY HE HAD A GREAT THIRST FOR KNOWLEDGE THAT NEVER LEFT HIM.
HE WAS THE FIRST TO GRADUATE HIGH SCHOOL AND COLLEGE.
AFTER GRADUATING COLLEGE HE BECAME A COLLEGE PROFESSOR.
HE WAS VERY PROUD TO SHOW HIS CLASSROOM WITH HIS NAME ON THE DOOR TO HIS FATHER.
HIS FATHER HAD ALWAYS WANTED HIM TO REACH AS HIGH AS HE COULD.
HE PROBABLY WOULDN'T HAVE BEEN IN THE SAME PLACE IF HE HADN'T SPENT HIS CHILDHOOD IN THE LIBRARY.
RAYMOND CLARK TOLD THE STORY ABOUT SAID LIBRARY.
AS A CHILD HE THOUGHT HE WAS RICH BUT HE WAS VERY POOR
HIS DAD GOT A JOB WORKING AS THE CUSTODIAN OF ONE LIBRARY.
THE FAMILY GOT TO LIVE IN THE LIBRARY

BUT IT WAS GREAT BECAUSE HE HAD MORE BOOKS THAN ANYONE.

HE WAS PROUD TO SHOW HIS FATHER HIS CLASSROOM AND HIS NAME ON THE DOOR
HE CAN'T IMAGINE WHERE HE WOULD HAVE BEEN IF HE DIDN'T LIVE IN THE LIBRARY.
